Writing a Dockerfile that works is straightforward. Writing one that produces small images, builds fast, and stays maintainable over time is a craft. This notebook covers the techniques that separate production-grade Dockerfiles from first drafts.

Layer Ordering: Maximise Cache Hits.

The build cache is your biggest lever for fast builds. The rule is simple: put things that change rarely near the top of the Dockerfile and things that change often near the bottom.

A cache miss at any layer invalidates every layer below it. If you copy all your application code before installing dependencies, then any code change — even a comment — triggers a full pip install or npm install on the next build.

The correct pattern is to copy only the dependency manifest first, then run the install command, then copy the rest of the application code. For Python this means copying requirements.txt, running pip install, and then copying the source files. For Node it means copying package.json and package-lock.json, running npm ci, and then copying the source. This way the install layer is cached on every rebuild that doesn't touch the dependency file — which is the vast majority of rebuilds during development.

Minimise Image Size.

Smaller images transfer faster, have a smaller attack surface, and start more quickly. Several techniques combine to reduce size.

The first is choosing a smaller base image. The full python image is around 340 megabytes compressed. The slim variant is around 45 megabytes. Alpine is around 18 megabytes but its use of musl libc causes compatibility issues with C-extension Python packages like numpy, pandas, and cryptography. Distroless images — which contain only the runtime and no shell or package manager — are around 15 megabytes and are ideal for production security.

The second technique is to install only what you need. Pass the --no-install-recommends flag to apt-get install to skip optional dependency packages that aren't required for your application.

The third technique is to clean up in the same RUN instruction. This point catches many people out: deleting files in a later RUN does not reduce image size. The files still exist in the earlier layer. The layer cache is additive — a delete in layer N plus one only adds a whiteout entry; the original bytes remain in layer N. You must chain the update, install, and cleanup into a single RUN using double ampersand so everything happens in one layer. The cleanup command for apt is rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/star.

Run as a Non-Root User.

By default, processes inside a container run as root — uid zero. If the container is compromised, the attacker has root inside the container namespace. Running as a non-root user limits the blast radius.

The pattern is to create a dedicated user and group with useradd and groupadd, use the chown flag on COPY instructions to assign ownership of files to that user, and then add a USER instruction to switch to that user before CMD and ENTRYPOINT. The USER instruction affects all subsequent instructions and the container's runtime process.

You can override the user at runtime with docker run --user root for debugging, without changing the image.

Pin Versions for Reproducibility.

Unpinned versions mean your build output can change silently when upstream packages are updated. Pin at every level. For the base image, specify the full version including the patch number and OS variant rather than a floating tag like python colon 3.12-slim. For Python packages, use exact equals-equals pins in requirements.txt, ideally generated by a tool like pip-compile that produces a fully resolved lockfile. For Node, commit package-lock.json and use npm ci instead of npm install — npm ci fails if the lockfile is out of sync with package.json, which is exactly the behaviour you want.

Keep Secrets Out of the Image.

Secrets embedded in images are a serious risk. They appear in layer history even if you delete them in a later RUN. This includes tokens passed as ARG values — docker history reveals them.

The right approach for build-time secrets is the BuildKit secret mount. You prefix your RUN instruction with --mount=type=secret and give the secret an id. At build time, you pass the secret with --secret id=name,src=filepath. During that RUN instruction, the secret is available as a file at /run/secrets/name. It is never written to any layer and never appears in docker history or docker inspect.

For runtime secrets — api keys, database passwords, service credentials — pass them via environment variables at docker run time, via a secrets manager, or via Docker secrets in Swarm mode. Never bake them into the image with ENV.

One Process Per Container.

Each container should run one main process. When PID 1 exits, the container exits. If you run multiple processes, the container lifecycle becomes ambiguous — which process dying should stop the container?

Beyond lifecycle, single-process containers give you cleaner logs, independent scaling, and targeted restarts. If you need multiple processes in one container, use a proper init system like tini as PID 1. Tini correctly reaps zombie processes and forwards signals to child processes. Docker also has a built-in init mode: docker run --init passes signals correctly without you needing to modify the Dockerfile.

Use HEALTHCHECK.

HEALTHCHECK tells Docker how to test whether the container is functioning correctly. The daemon runs the check periodically and marks the container healthy or unhealthy. You configure the interval, timeout, start period, and retry count.

A typical health check for a web service uses curl to hit a dedicated health endpoint and exits with code 1 if the request fails. The start period is a grace time that allows the application to start up before health check failures start counting.

Orchestrators including Kubernetes and Docker Swarm use health status to decide whether to route traffic to a container and whether to restart it. A container that is running but unhealthy gets no traffic.

Lint with hadolint.

hadolint is a Dockerfile linter that catches common mistakes automatically: missing --no-install-recommends, unpinned apt packages, use of ADD where COPY would do, running apt-get update in a separate layer from apt-get install, and more. You can run it as a Docker container, which means no local installation is needed. Each warning has an identifier you can use to suppress specific rules where you have a deliberate reason to deviate.

Integrating hadolint in ci-cd means Dockerfile anti-patterns are caught before they reach production.

Summary.

Order layers with dependency manifests before application code so the install step is cached across code-only rebuilds.

Keep images small by choosing a slim base, using --no-install-recommends, and cleaning up package caches in the same RUN layer — cleanup in a later layer does not shrink the image.

Run as a non-root user: create a dedicated user, set ownership with COPY --chown, and switch with USER.

Pin the base image tag to an exact version, and pin all application dependencies with lockfiles.

Never put secrets in ENV or ARG — use --mount=type=secret at build time and a secrets manager at runtime.

One process per container. Add a HEALTHCHECK so orchestrators can detect unhealthy containers. Lint with hadolint in ci-cd to catch anti-patterns automatically.

